21:41.922 --> 21:46.607
I have been married almost 30 years and I haven't touched a thermostat in almost 30 years.

21:47.068 --> 21:50.512
So let that be lesson number one today.

21:50.572 --> 21:53.615
My wife was born in Austin, Minnesota.

21:53.635 --> 22:00.102
And at the age of six, Hormel went on strike and my father-in-law moved the family to Fremont, Nebraska.

22:00.142 --> 22:03.326
So that's where my wife spent most of her childhood.

22:03.366 --> 22:07.090
And this past week, I had an event in Sioux Falls, South Dakota.

22:07.586 --> 22:19.159
We were married in Fremont and I looked at Amy and I said, wouldn't it be fun to leave a little bit early and go do a hometown tour and show me all around Fremont Nebraska?

22:19.199 --> 22:20.761
And she said, why?

22:20.801 --> 22:32.694
And then I promised myself I wasn't going to sing this weekend, but if you ever had a song in your heart and it just has to come out, and this country song by Rascal Flats came to mind and I sang it right to her.

22:32.774 --> 22:36.658
I said, there's a place in your heart, nobody's been.

22:36.994 --> 22:37.915
Take me there.

22:39.537 --> 22:41.680
Things, nobody knows, not even your friends.

22:41.760 --> 22:42.421
Take me there.

22:42.461 --> 22:45.165
Tell me about your mama, your daddy, your hometown.

22:45.325 --> 22:46.126
Show me around.

22:46.187 --> 22:51.093
I want to see it all, which only takes about 20 minutes in Fremont, Nebraska.

22:52.675 --> 22:53.797
And so we did.

22:53.917 --> 22:57.001
We went to Fremont, and she says, let's make this quick.

22:57.903 --> 23:01.748
And we went to the Dairy Queen, where she worked.

23:01.788 --> 23:06.354
We went to the house that she grew up in, and we ended the tour at the church.

23:06.594 --> 23:11.002
where we were married, it'll be 30 years this October, and we got in the car.

23:11.022 --> 23:14.127
And I'm the more sentimental one in our marriage, I get that.

23:14.788 --> 23:16.932
And she looked at me and she says, are you good?

23:19.958 --> 23:20.699
And I said, I'm good.

23:20.719 --> 23:21.480
She goes, punch it.

23:21.520 --> 23:22.582
We got to get to Sioux Falls.

23:22.642 --> 23:26.469
So I am still learning about my wife.

23:26.609 --> 23:28.092
That's why I love doing tours like that.

23:28.112 --> 23:30.256
And on the way out, I said, hey, there's a cemetery.

23:30.276 --> 23:31.538
Do we need to go see anyone?

23:32.194 --> 23:34.036
And she said, we're good, let's go.

23:34.056 --> 23:42.064
I said, but these are the moments, 30 years into marriage that we can take to still learn something about one another.

23:42.084 --> 23:50.692
And I don't know if you've ever had a relationship that you poured yourself into and the other person never really received it.

23:51.253 --> 23:55.237
Could be a parent, a child, a spouse, it could be a co-worker, a friend.

23:55.977 --> 23:58.500
And you think to yourself, I'm saying all the right things.

23:58.540 --> 24:00.882
I feel like I'm doing the right stuff

24:01.410 --> 24:03.132
But it's just not connecting.

24:03.994 --> 24:06.117
We see this with newlyweds all the time.

24:06.778 --> 24:12.526
Because early in romantic relationship formation, we tend to downplay our differences, okay?

24:12.726 --> 24:17.333
And we shine a spotlight on the things we have in common and our similarities.

24:17.393 --> 24:25.665
But a year or two into marriage, we start thinking, okay, why is what worked in dating and engagement not working now?

24:26.727 --> 24:29.170
I see it in the counseling office all the time.

24:29.442 --> 24:33.506
A husband will list for me everything he does around the house.

24:34.487 --> 24:38.692
And all the stuff he does to take care of the car and everything he does to take care of the family.

24:38.732 --> 24:49.083
And I look over to the wife and she says, I don't feel loved, I don't feel heard, I don't feel cared for, I don't feel valued.

24:50.004 --> 24:55.730
And it's for all those reasons that this weekend, I'm excited for us to look at the love languages.

24:55.938 --> 24:59.482
Dr. Gary Chapman released the Five Love Languages book in 1992.

24:59.642 --> 25:03.266
It's the best-selling marriage book of all time.

25:04.047 --> 25:11.335
And last year, Dr. Chapman and Dr. Isles and Leslie Parrot invited me to join the Five Love Languages teaching team.

25:11.975 --> 25:20.104
And I dove in, not just to be a part of the team, but I wanted to learn more about the love languages for Amy and I in our marriage.

25:20.524 --> 25:25.650
And what I didn't know up until last year is that there are 22 dialects

25:25.826 --> 25:27.488
underneath the five love languages.

25:27.908 --> 25:32.072
I meet people all the time, they've never read the book, but they can tell me what their love language is.

25:32.773 --> 25:39.220
These dialects, they're what helps us from having things get lost in translation.

25:39.720 --> 25:47.969
For example, a couple years ago, I was in London with my family, we were at a store, I went up to the cashier, and I asked, where is your nearest restroom?

25:48.710 --> 25:50.491
And she said, what's your preference?

25:52.133 --> 25:53.074
I said mail.

25:54.818 --> 25:57.001
And we stood there in awkward silence.

25:58.462 --> 26:00.645
Something was getting lost in translation.

26:00.785 --> 26:03.949
She thought I asked, where's your nearest restaurant?

26:08.694 --> 26:09.675
We weren't connecting.

26:10.496 --> 26:13.740
I don't know if you know this about England, but they speak English there.

26:14.961 --> 26:19.026
We speak English, but we don't have the same dialect.

26:19.618 --> 26:27.569
And even when you know your spouse's love language, if you don't know the nuance or the dialect to dial in, things get lost.

26:28.391 --> 26:34.299
In their latest book, Doctors Chapman and Parrot wrote called, The Love Language That Matters Most.

26:34.319 --> 26:40.588
They tell the story of a husband who knew his wife was gonna be coming home late from a long day of meetings.

26:41.549 --> 26:47.538
And so he thought, I'm gonna really lean into her love language, which was acts of service.

26:47.682 --> 26:51.548
and I'm gonna get home and I'm gonna prepare a nice gourmet meal.

26:52.209 --> 26:54.312
He spent hours making this meal.

26:54.392 --> 27:05.890
We're talking tablecloth, candles on the table, lights them, she walks through the door, exhausted, and he's basically like, voila!

27:06.271 --> 27:09.316
And she's like, ugh.

27:09.336 --> 27:12.461
This isn't at all what I was wanting when I got home.

27:13.562 --> 27:15.826
I prefer those candles around the bathtub.

27:16.770 --> 27:22.639
Because on the way home, I was thinking about a bath, sweatpants, and bed.

27:23.821 --> 27:29.329
He had the right heart, and he knew her love language, but it was the dialect that meant everything.

27:29.369 --> 27:31.753
So here's what we hear all the time with couples.

27:32.354 --> 27:34.677
Oh, this is gonna be a wonderful weekend.

27:34.837 --> 27:37.862
I hope he really pays attention.

27:38.803 --> 27:43.250
I hope she really listens because she needs to learn more about me.

27:44.066 --> 27:45.968
He needs to learn more about me.

27:45.988 --> 27:50.753
And some of you might be in a place in your marriage after years that you're in drift.

27:51.314 --> 27:52.175
Not all that happy.

27:52.195 --> 27:53.516
You don't feel like you're connecting.

27:53.536 --> 27:57.040
Love tanks pretty low and you're wanting some change.

27:57.080 --> 27:59.002
And so here's where we're starting this weekend.

27:59.283 --> 28:02.987
If you don't like what you're getting out of your marriage, change what you put into it.

28:04.048 --> 28:04.669
Let's go home.

28:05.189 --> 28:06.951
That's really all we need to know right there.

28:06.991 --> 28:10.595
That's called personal responsibility.

28:11.797 --> 28:13.138
That's learning.

28:13.346 --> 28:18.611
about your spouse so you can change your serve, not your spouse.

28:19.672 --> 28:21.234
I love props, you know I love props.

28:21.334 --> 28:36.328
I keep a ping pong paddle and ping pong balls in my office and to make this point right here because when I hear couples going at each other and like just real harsh and demanding toward each other, I'll just grab a ping pong paddle and take the ping pong balls and go, whap, and I'll start hitting them with ping pong.

28:36.409 --> 28:39.972
I'm very, I want a real engaged counseling session.

28:40.613 --> 28:42.034
And they start going like this.

28:42.370 --> 28:45.454
And I'm like, that's what I, that's how you guys are coming across to each other right now.

28:45.474 --> 28:47.096
You're slamming this serve.

28:47.717 --> 28:49.299
I wanna encourage you to change your serve.

28:49.319 --> 28:50.961
And then I'll say, it's real simple.

28:50.981 --> 28:53.845
And then I'll start lobbing it to them.

28:53.865 --> 28:56.308
Instead of sitting there, I wish he'd open up, I wish he'd talk.

28:56.348 --> 29:00.814
When he gets home, I never get, how about just, try a lob.

29:01.935 --> 29:03.317
Change what you put into it.

29:03.337 --> 29:06.261
Now you've heard it said, Ted, it takes two.

29:06.761 --> 29:07.562
I know it takes two.

29:07.662 --> 29:10.546
It takes two, but it often starts with one.

29:11.362 --> 29:15.388
And this weekend, I'm hoping you make the decision to be the one to make the change.

29:16.390 --> 29:20.656
But I want to take us first to the words of Jesus to remind us why we're even doing this.

29:20.676 --> 29:22.339
Why are we even talking about love languages?

29:23.320 --> 29:32.694
In a very important Bible study method, when you're reading the Bible, when you see repetition, I always tell people, go back and reread because repetition is there for emphasis.

29:33.315 --> 29:37.181
And watch what Jesus says, a new command I give you, love one another.

29:37.221 --> 29:40.306
As I have loved you, so you must,

29:40.514 --> 29:41.355
Love one another.

29:42.637 --> 29:47.302
By this, everyone will know that you are my disciples if you love one another.

29:47.422 --> 29:49.845
Here's the outline of what Jesus just shared.

29:50.706 --> 29:52.668
This is commanded, Jesus commanded it.

29:52.688 --> 29:57.975
He modeled it, and this is what I love about the love language, just conversation.

29:58.015 --> 30:07.666
We know we're called to love one another, but the love language just teaches how, how to better love those in our life, how to better love spouse, children, parents, friends,

30:08.482 --> 30:10.284
And so Jesus modeled this.

30:10.304 --> 30:13.207
He shows, if you read the gospel, he used physical touch.

30:13.247 --> 30:15.350
He placed hands on the sick to heal them.

30:15.610 --> 30:19.194
When the disciples tried to keep the children from Jesus, he grew in dignity.

30:19.254 --> 30:22.778
He brought the children to him, placed his hands on them and blessed them.

30:23.619 --> 30:28.644
When the disciples were trying to figure things out, Jesus used words of affirmation to say, take heart.

30:30.967 --> 30:34.050
The Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve.

30:34.811 --> 30:37.234
He ultimately gave his life.

30:38.434 --> 30:43.661
And when you think of quality time, Jesus, oh, plenty of times we read him, getting alone with the disciples.

30:43.801 --> 30:48.948
I even love how the Bible says there were times he got away so that no one knew where they were.

30:49.008 --> 30:52.193
That's so that he could have quality time with them.

30:52.353 --> 30:54.536
Jesus showed us how to do this.

30:54.816 --> 30:56.619
He modeled it for us.

30:57.460 --> 31:04.850
And when we learn how to love one another better, it points other people to Jesus.

31:05.570 --> 31:11.536
And so the question we're gonna answer hopefully this weekend for you to encourage you is what is a love language?

31:12.317 --> 31:14.078
When we use this term, what is a love language?

31:14.118 --> 31:17.041
Some people, and you're probably most common when we hear is chocolate.

31:17.902 --> 31:19.684
Chocolate is my love language.

31:20.745 --> 31:25.229
And I would say every time people throw me a love language, they're like, oh, Dr. Chapman missed one.

31:25.249 --> 31:31.335
I think the sixth love language is typically it fits within one of the other five love languages.

31:31.415 --> 31:34.418
And now with the dialects that we have, you can dig even

31:34.530 --> 31:38.274
And if you make somebody chocolate, right, that is an act of service.

31:38.314 --> 31:41.297
If you give them chocolate, that's receiving gifts.

31:41.317 --> 31:43.179
I would probably wear this shirt right here.

31:43.219 --> 31:46.883
I've said for years, sarcasm is the sixth love language.

31:48.465 --> 31:49.947
But it's not a love language.

31:49.967 --> 31:52.830
My wife actually believes this right here.

31:52.870 --> 31:55.252
Fast delivery is my love language.

31:56.974 --> 32:04.242
But this is important, because you might see boxes on the front step and go, oh, well, she loves gifts.

32:04.578 --> 32:07.902
I learned this last year, 30 years of marriage.

32:07.922 --> 32:12.807
You have to, this is what's so important about never, never stop learning about your spouse.

32:13.728 --> 32:21.017
My wife, I've always known she has two love languages, acts of service and quality time, which means I serve her for long periods of time.

32:21.037 --> 32:25.562
That's what these two love languages coming together mean.

32:26.263 --> 32:27.544
But I didn't know her dialects.

32:28.125 --> 32:30.868
And that's where things would get lost in translation for us.

32:30.908 --> 32:32.850
And her primary dialect,

32:33.314 --> 32:35.838
under acts of service is saving time.

32:37.020 --> 32:49.899
Anything she can do to save time, anything I can do to help her save time is, so every time I see a box, I realize she got something that saved her an hour trip to the store.

32:51.021 --> 32:54.386
Okay, so this is true of every single person in here.

32:55.170 --> 32:58.935
This is true of every single person across all of our campuses and watching online.

32:59.035 --> 33:00.517
We know the next two things to be true.

33:00.977 --> 33:04.261
Our deepest emotional need is to feel loved.

33:05.723 --> 33:12.431
Every person you meet today wants to be seen, heard, valued, cared for, and loved.

33:14.354 --> 33:16.496
But this is where love languages come in.

33:16.516 --> 33:17.698
It's where it gets a little tricky.

33:17.978 --> 33:21.222
We all feel loved in different ways.

33:22.544 --> 33:24.466
This is why we need to learn the how.

33:24.546 --> 33:25.107
behind it.

33:25.207 --> 33:31.734
For example, some of you today, there are ladies in here, you love it when he brings you home flowers.

33:32.555 --> 33:34.857
You're like, that is the most romantic thing he can do.

33:35.798 --> 33:36.479
Not for Amy.

33:37.700 --> 33:38.601
I bring her flowers.

33:38.721 --> 33:39.662
She says, thank you.

33:41.084 --> 33:53.998
We all are somewhere with all of these love languages, and she'll say thank you, but it doesn't feel, it gives baby puts a little under the love tank, but doesn't feel it like acts of service or quality time, and she'll take and go, thank you, give me a kiss, put him in the vase and walk off.

33:54.018 --> 33:54.418
I'm like,

33:54.498 --> 33:56.360
Let's come back to the flowers for just a second.

33:58.062 --> 34:00.364
Now I probably have to tell you how much I paid for these flowers.

34:01.505 --> 34:05.349
And the time it took me to get them, because you just don't seem, but that's not Amy.

34:06.410 --> 34:17.502
Amy, let me tell you, Amy, I love when we're in the family room at night and watching something, she'll grab her phone and she'll start typing in and she'll look over at me and she'll say, thank you.

34:18.242 --> 34:18.863
And I'll say, what?

34:18.943 --> 34:21.906
She goes, you just got me something real nice.

34:24.322 --> 34:26.125
You know what romance is in our home?

34:26.626 --> 34:27.608
Cutting out the middleman.

34:27.688 --> 34:28.890
That's romance in our home.

34:29.892 --> 34:31.735
And I just say you're welcome and we move on.

34:31.775 --> 34:32.556
Here's another one.

34:33.197 --> 34:37.745
This is not Amy Cunningham or Ted Cunningham's primary love language.

34:37.765 --> 34:38.807
We ain't cuddlers.

34:39.709 --> 34:40.430
We don't cuddle.

34:41.312 --> 34:42.514
We know we probably should.

34:42.554 --> 34:43.616
We see people do it.

34:45.078 --> 34:48.684
You see it in TV and movies and we know in Minnesota this means survival.

34:48.805 --> 34:49.586
I get that.

34:52.226 --> 34:57.312
But they're just, physical touch is a foreign love language for us.

34:58.273 --> 35:01.077
But there are times I'll look at her and be like, hey, let's cuddle.

35:01.738 --> 35:02.438
She's like, all right.

35:04.841 --> 35:06.263
And I'll get on the couch with her.

35:06.403 --> 35:12.851
And both of us at the same time after about a minute and a half are like, get off of me, I'm hot.

35:12.871 --> 35:13.872
My arms asleep.

35:17.417 --> 35:18.818
Yeah, so it's just, it's not us.

35:18.838 --> 35:21.842
But let me tell you what does fill my wife's love tank.

35:22.050 --> 35:24.133
Just pull out the planning calendar.

35:26.457 --> 35:29.261
You know what January one looks like in our home every year?

35:29.301 --> 35:33.728
January one is an all day planning meeting in the Cunningham home.

35:35.330 --> 35:42.721
And I mean, all of our schedules, all of our plans, Amy, she starts preparing for it in the middle of December.

35:42.781 --> 35:48.249
We bring in the new year, but then we get up that morning and Amy is like, she's rocking back and forth ready to go.

35:48.289 --> 35:50.333
And I'm like, oh, let's do this.

35:50.353 --> 35:51.314
Not my thing.

35:53.410 --> 35:54.311
But you know why I do it?

35:54.431 --> 35:55.052
It's her thing.

35:56.093 --> 35:59.037
She wants this and it fills her love tank.

35:59.057 --> 36:00.459
You know what fills my love tank?

36:00.499 --> 36:01.220
It's real simple.

36:01.641 --> 36:03.803
A note that just says thank you for working so hard.

36:05.245 --> 36:07.648
There are three dialects under words of affirmation.

36:08.269 --> 36:11.954
Compliments, appreciation, and encouragement.

36:12.314 --> 36:13.636
And I'll be honest with you, I like them all.

36:14.918 --> 36:16.440
They're all part of my dialects.

36:16.480 --> 36:21.426
But you begin to dial them in a little bit more as we go through.

36:21.634 --> 36:29.666
Your love language, as we answer this question, your love language comes down to how you best receive love from others.

36:31.069 --> 36:38.480
But if Dr. Chapman were standing on this stage right here, he would tell you, he doesn't want you to learn the love languages so you can know yours only.

36:39.381 --> 36:45.010
He wants you to become fluent in all five so you can better love other people.

36:45.986 --> 36:47.067
So that's the love lines.

36:47.087 --> 36:53.516
And I want to go through them again real quick, give you a definition, break down some of the dialects, wish we could do a deep dive into them.

36:53.996 --> 36:58.562
For those students in the room, you're going to probably leave here and dig into them even more.

36:58.582 --> 37:01.125
But I'm going to start with the most important love.

37:01.185 --> 37:02.427
No, that's not the most important love lines.

37:02.447 --> 37:04.550
But I do.

37:04.930 --> 37:11.218
But even within the complement dialect, there are things I like to be complimented on.

37:11.426 --> 37:19.055
like things I've done, and sometimes it can be achievements, but let me tell you where I don't need a compliment for the way I look, for the way I dress.

37:20.296 --> 37:24.341
I don't need to be told, and you can probably, I'm not the biggest fashion guy on the planet.

37:25.322 --> 37:31.889
And I can come out in the morning, putting a lot of thought into what I'm gonna wear for the day, and I'll walk into the kitchen and Amy will be like, ooh.

37:34.272 --> 37:36.054
She'll like, are you wearing that today?

37:36.074 --> 37:39.378
And I'm like, no, I just put this on for breakfast.

37:42.178 --> 37:44.241
I'm going to change before I leave the house.

37:44.301 --> 37:45.543
I would never go out in this.

37:45.583 --> 37:46.143
And then I walk away.

37:46.244 --> 37:49.288
I have no, but that doesn't, it doesn't drain me, doesn't film.

37:49.328 --> 37:51.591
It's just not, it's not what I'm looking for.

37:51.631 --> 37:56.718
Mark Twain said, I can make it two months on one good compliment.

37:58.260 --> 38:01.565
And let me tell you, this is fuel for those with words of affirmation.

38:02.546 --> 38:04.309
Encouragement is you got this.

38:05.110 --> 38:06.612
Appreciation is thank you.

38:07.373 --> 38:11.058
If this is your spouse's love language or a child's love language,

38:11.554 --> 38:15.599
you would be shocked at how far a thank you goes.

38:16.540 --> 38:17.361
How far a thank you goes.

38:17.381 --> 38:17.962
Let's move on.

38:17.982 --> 38:18.783
Amy and I both.

38:19.084 --> 38:20.465
My next one is quality time.

38:20.485 --> 38:23.629
This is her primary love language.

38:24.210 --> 38:29.677
And the dialects, there's four dialects under quality time, scheduled and unscheduled.

38:29.797 --> 38:31.499
And Amy is scheduled.

38:31.579 --> 38:32.581
I am unscheduled.

38:32.641 --> 38:34.243
I like to be spontaneous.

38:34.303 --> 38:37.968
I like things to pop up during the day and be like, whoa, what a great surprise.

38:38.008 --> 38:39.890
Let's go in that direction.

38:40.226 --> 38:43.610
I put plans together and if they work great, if they don't, I'm okay with that.

38:44.291 --> 38:50.178
Future-oriented and present-oriented are two of the other dialects, and Amy and I are both future-oriented.

38:51.059 --> 38:58.128
But the key with this, words of affirmation is receiving love through written or spoken words.

38:58.508 --> 39:05.417
Quality time is receiving love through meaningful conversation and shared activities.

39:05.937 --> 39:07.399
So here's where you really have to dial it in.

39:07.479 --> 39:09.682
What shared activity works best for you?

39:10.178 --> 39:13.382
I've heard from couples that we love playing board games, Ted.

39:14.123 --> 39:16.585
And we have great conversations while playing board games.

39:16.686 --> 39:24.174
The problem with that in our marriage and in our family is none of us are speaking to each other after playing board games.

39:24.194 --> 39:26.857
We're a highly aggressive and competitive family.

39:27.939 --> 39:33.145
And nothing brings greater joy to my soul as a dad than bankrupting my children in Monopoly.

39:33.245 --> 39:34.226
I live for it.

39:36.034 --> 39:38.257
Amy will look at me and be like, you go easy on them.

39:38.337 --> 39:39.299
Go easy on them.

39:39.319 --> 39:41.442
Is the real world going to go easy on them?

39:42.023 --> 39:46.189
I will wipe every hotel and house off this board and foreclose on every last property.

39:46.209 --> 39:48.072
They're going to learn some hard lessons here today.

39:49.414 --> 39:54.161
You've seen that video online of that kid crying after getting wiped out of Monopoly and mom goes, honey, what's the matter?

39:54.181 --> 39:55.283
And he goes, taxes.

39:58.708 --> 39:59.710
Honey, it's just a game.

39:59.750 --> 40:02.214
It's the worst part of the game, taxes.

40:03.455 --> 40:05.138
So that's not our shared activity.

40:06.050 --> 40:12.056
And by the way, with quality time, the activity is not as important as the conversation.

40:12.617 --> 40:18.783
So if words of affirmation is speaking, quality time's really about what can I do to get your undivided attention?

40:19.764 --> 40:22.206
And Amy and I found our shared activity this past summer.

40:23.027 --> 40:28.473
We would always do this, but we didn't realize how valuable this was for us and filled both of us up.

40:29.214 --> 40:30.655
My wife hates driving.

40:30.715 --> 40:33.618
She can't stand driving because she could be doing something else.

40:34.370 --> 40:35.612
She could be getting work done.

40:35.752 --> 40:37.735
She could be sending a text, sending an email.

40:38.536 --> 40:42.441
And so when I drive her to do errands, she loves it.

40:42.461 --> 40:44.004
She goes, I got these five places to go.

40:44.224 --> 40:47.088
Since I don't like shopping, I drop her off at the door at Target.

40:47.549 --> 40:51.354
She goes in, I go parking the no parking zone, revving the engine, waiting for it to go.

40:51.394 --> 40:55.059
And then I see her come out and I pick her up and we're off to the next thing.

40:55.079 --> 40:56.121
She says, thank you, babe.

40:56.421 --> 40:57.903
So she's speaking my language.

40:57.983 --> 40:58.624
I'm saving her.

40:58.844 --> 40:59.646
We're getting it done.

41:01.068 --> 41:02.770
What is your shared activity?

41:02.850 --> 41:10.018
Because Amy's next, she has two primary, two primary love languages, and her next one is acts of service.

41:10.138 --> 41:13.782
The four dialects under acts of service are instilling security.

41:13.802 --> 41:25.915
And for some of you, maybe an early romantic relationship formation, when this person speaks your love language, they're saying to you with that, I prioritize this relationship.

41:26.416 --> 41:28.919
You're important to me, I'm here for the long haul.

41:28.979 --> 41:32.082
For others, a dialect may be alleviating stress.

41:32.994 --> 41:37.959
They like the lady in the first story I shared today who just wanted a bath and bed.

41:38.019 --> 41:39.280
That's all she was looking for.

41:39.300 --> 41:41.563
Others that can be conveying care.

41:42.664 --> 41:45.426
So an act of service could be bed and breakfast.

41:45.987 --> 41:48.309
Breakfast, bed and breakfast, that'd be kind of awkward.

41:48.550 --> 41:49.431
Breakfast in bed.

41:49.471 --> 41:59.220
But let me tell you, I know that's not one way to love Amy because if I tie her up and keep her schedule and I have the breakfast there, she's like, I could be getting stuff done.

41:59.401 --> 42:00.882
Do I have to sit here and eat this?

42:01.090 --> 42:02.091
That's not her dialect.

42:02.151 --> 42:06.236
Her dialect is the fourth, saving time, saving time.

42:06.736 --> 42:08.478
The next one is receiving gifts.

42:08.558 --> 42:11.061
Both of my children have this as their primary love language.

42:13.163 --> 42:14.565
True, true.

42:14.605 --> 42:15.225
And you know what I want?

42:15.245 --> 42:27.058
You know, if acts of service is receiving love through someone else's time to save you time, someone else's energy to save you time and to make your life easier.

42:27.714 --> 42:33.401
Receiving gifts is receiving these tangible expressions, gifts that say two things.

42:33.902 --> 42:36.284
You were thinking of me and you know me.

42:37.326 --> 42:38.727
You were thinking of me and you know me.

42:38.747 --> 42:42.072
And the dialects under this, my son and daughter have very different dialects.

42:42.112 --> 42:43.573
My daughter is the sentimental one.

42:44.154 --> 42:50.602
So she moves towards the dialect of simple and heartfelt.

42:50.622 --> 42:54.827
So when I would travel and if I brought back a magnet from the state, I was just in.

42:54.867 --> 42:57.170
She'd be like, this is the best thing ever, thank you.

42:57.442 --> 43:03.592
Daddy, but my son, he's a little more extravagant in the dialect and functional.

43:03.632 --> 43:04.513
He likes watches.

43:05.174 --> 43:07.438
And I tell him, think Timex not Rolex.

43:07.478 --> 43:09.301
That's where we're going with this.

43:10.883 --> 43:13.708
But I want you to know, this is the foreign love language.

43:13.768 --> 43:15.991
Receiving gifts is the foreign love language for most people.

43:16.833 --> 43:20.899
If this is your primary love language, this doesn't mean you're materialistic.

43:21.780 --> 43:23.383
That's not what that means at all.

43:24.665 --> 43:25.426
The next one.

43:25.698 --> 43:33.708
Physical touch actually has the most dialects with seven dialects, but this is receiving love when words fall short.

43:35.029 --> 43:43.700
It can be comforting touch at a funeral when someone has passed away and you don't know what to say that you just walk up and you stand near someone.

43:44.861 --> 43:46.183
You put your arm around them.

43:47.084 --> 43:55.314
It can be romantic, comforting, playful, ooh, I've told Amy, listen, when my wife tickles me,

43:55.970 --> 43:57.353
That's hate, not love.

43:58.977 --> 44:01.303
Because this is not my primary love language.

44:02.145 --> 44:03.428
There's protective touch.

44:04.209 --> 44:09.201
I like to walk on the side of the street from people, you know, to protect them from cars coming in.

44:09.402 --> 44:14.674
Maybe going into a store, you grab an arm and put the hand on the small of the back of your offering that protective touch.

44:16.194 --> 44:18.717
affectionate touch, all these great dialects.

44:18.737 --> 44:24.665
And I'm hoping one thing sticks out today so that you can answer this question sometime this week.

44:24.965 --> 44:28.489
What are some new ways I can show up for you?

44:29.651 --> 44:39.343
Not how I can get my tank filled, but what are some new ways I can show up for you in our marriage, in our relationship?

44:40.084 --> 44:45.170
My primary love language is how I best receive and feel love.

44:45.250 --> 44:50.638
but I want to become fluent in all five to better love others.

44:50.658 --> 45:10.006
I've been on this, I've made my kids take these assessments, I've made staff, I've asked church and I've asked people, I want to see your reports, I want to know what your love language is and your dialects and one of our staff guys came up to me and he goes, I'm kind of embarrassed to tell you this, but my primary love language is physical touch and I go, come here buddy, that's okay, I'll get you.

45:11.187 --> 45:13.010
If you need a hug and it's not mine,

45:13.218 --> 45:17.484
So I, and I don't need a hug, but if you want one, bring it in.

45:17.524 --> 45:18.426
I'm gonna give you one.

45:18.706 --> 45:21.971
But then he goes, no, no, no, I don't want you to start hugging me every time you see me.

45:23.694 --> 45:27.279
His is more of that affectionate touch.

45:27.579 --> 45:36.312
His is more of the, when I walk into a meeting and he's sitting there, if I walk by him and just take my fist and kind of tap him on the shoulder, that just says, I see you're here.

45:36.953 --> 45:38.576
I just recognized you in the room.

45:39.397 --> 45:42.802
It's a high five sometimes after a great shot in golf

45:42.946 --> 45:51.018
This particular staff member just got the biggest trout at Dogwood Canyon and I was able to net it for him and there were multiple high fives during that.

45:51.079 --> 45:56.547
So you're finding out and becoming fluent in this and saying, I might not be comfortable with this one.

45:56.948 --> 45:58.670
This isn't my thing, that's okay.

45:59.672 --> 46:03.598
But Jesus modeled for us how to love others well.

46:04.079 --> 46:07.524
And I wanna become fluent in all five to better love other people.

46:07.544 --> 46:11.410
You've heard it said that love is a decision, not a feeling.

46:11.874 --> 46:19.005
A better way to say it is love is more than a feeling because love is a decision and a feeling.

46:19.846 --> 46:22.270
That's what I want the takeaway to be today.

46:22.590 --> 46:24.253
Love is a decision and a feeling.

46:24.293 --> 46:30.422
And so when you put this, I've been using the terms primary and foreign love language.

46:31.143 --> 46:36.872
I want us to get into understanding the next step for me as I find new ways to show up for you.

46:36.892 --> 46:38.514
So if you go back to this scale,

46:39.074 --> 46:43.559
right here, and I'm going to put them in order for you of Ted Cunningham.

46:43.860 --> 46:52.650
I shared with you words of affirmation as primary, quality time right behind that, acts of service at the far end, receiving gifts and physical touch.

46:53.911 --> 47:00.119
The reason why this is important is because love is a decision and a feeling.

47:00.199 --> 47:03.122
Stick with that for just a second as you start to think about, okay,

47:03.234 --> 47:04.416
This really fills me up.

47:04.436 --> 47:05.198
I really like this.

47:05.358 --> 47:10.348
This not so much, but it might be a secondary and I don't want to neglect that in your life.

47:11.871 --> 47:16.700
In the song of songs, two, five, we read, sustain me with raisins, refresh me with apples.

47:17.682 --> 47:22.892
I love to share this passage because this is what we call the tingles or the sparks, for I am sick with love.

47:22.992 --> 47:23.954
That is a feeling.

47:25.122 --> 47:26.223
Love is a feeling.

47:26.244 --> 47:29.788
You have a physical reaction to a person that you love, but guess what?

47:30.069 --> 47:33.153
After you've been married for 30 years, you're not always feeling it.

47:34.394 --> 47:37.539
And it's at that moment you have to be reminded of your decision.

47:37.599 --> 47:47.452
And that's when the foreign love language and the secondary love language comes in and say, I'm gonna become fluent in all five to better love other people.

47:48.333 --> 47:52.018
Receiving love through your primary love language is a feeling.

47:53.154 --> 47:56.618
I felt heard, I felt seen, I felt loved, I felt cared for.

47:56.678 --> 48:01.883
But giving love through your foreign love language is a decision.

48:03.064 --> 48:08.050
And that's the decision I'm hoping we're making this weekend as we find new ways to show up for one another.

48:08.810 --> 48:19.762
What I want to do to close out our time, almost like an introduction or a primer to the love language, is walk you through the song of songs and show you how all five love languages are in there.

48:20.514 --> 48:23.217
I've been seeing it in the life of Jesus as I read the Bible.

48:23.237 --> 48:25.880
I'm like, where does that fit with the love languages?

48:26.021 --> 48:29.505
And when you get into the song of songs, they jump off the page.

48:29.545 --> 48:36.573
If you're unfamiliar with this Old Testament book, it's Hebrew poetry, and it's the duet between Solomon and the Shulomite woman.

48:37.334 --> 48:39.697
Chapters one and two, they're dating, courting.

48:39.817 --> 48:41.299
Chapter three, they get married.

48:41.800 --> 48:43.402
Chapter four, they're at the J.W.

48:43.442 --> 48:44.904
Marriott for the honeymoon.

48:45.965 --> 48:50.290
Chapters five through eight, they're building faithfulness and commitment into

48:50.402 --> 48:50.983
the marriage.

48:52.405 --> 48:58.353
And so words of affirmation probably jump off the page the most because it's these lyrics going back and forth.

48:58.393 --> 49:01.498
And we read how beautiful you are, my darling, oh, how beautiful.

49:01.538 --> 49:03.000
This is Solomon speaking to her.

49:03.280 --> 49:06.305
Your eyes are doves.

49:08.187 --> 49:10.390
He begins praising her beauty.

49:10.430 --> 49:12.914
When you get to the Song of Songs chapter 4,

49:13.346 --> 49:14.547
They're at the honeymoon.

49:14.588 --> 49:17.051
She begins undressing in front of her husband.

49:17.351 --> 49:23.418
He's praising her beauty that when you get to verse seven of chapter four, he says, you are altogether beautiful, my darling.

49:23.438 --> 49:26.422
And it's what every single wife in here wants to hear.

49:26.462 --> 49:30.627
It's what every single wife watching across our campuses want to hear.

49:30.647 --> 49:33.831
I am altogether beautiful.

49:34.312 --> 49:37.355
You obviously see physical touch throughout the book.

49:37.375 --> 49:42.802
Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth for your love is more delightful than wine.

49:43.586 --> 49:51.075
I love this in chapter two, verse six, his left arm is under my head and his right arm embraces me.

49:51.115 --> 49:54.940
I don't know if you get active when you read the Bible, but sometimes you got to act this stuff out.

49:57.062 --> 49:58.624
And I love walking into the kitchen.

49:58.644 --> 50:02.269
I mean, you see that was a different type of walk.

50:02.289 --> 50:03.911
That wasn't just how I walked out here early.

50:05.072 --> 50:06.754
Let me try that again.

50:06.774 --> 50:07.976
That felt real awkward.

50:08.056 --> 50:09.778
She got real uncomfortable down there.

50:13.378 --> 50:14.860
So, I can't even do it now.

50:15.000 --> 50:17.082
So, babe, how's that?

